WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.101 --> 00:00:02.169
[R.J.]
<i>Previously on</i> R.J. Decker...

2
00:00:02.302 --> 00:00:03.437
You wanted to see me?

3
00:00:03.571 --> 00:00:05.540
You can stay here one week.
and then you go.

4
00:00:05.673 --> 00:00:08.710
I don't need some pretend PI
looking over my shoulder.

5
00:00:08.843 --> 00:00:10.678
let alone one flopping
in my pool house.

6
00:00:10.812 --> 00:00:13.313
[Wish] <i>Need I remind you.</i>
<i>you're on conditional release.</i>

7
00:00:13.447 --> 00:00:16.116
You get caught breaking
into a car. they'll violate you
back to prison.

8
00:00:16.250 --> 00:00:18.553
-I was just
in the neighborhood--
-You want something.

9
00:00:18.686 --> 00:00:22.389
Where would the FLPD
be without the help
of low-rent PIs?

10
00:00:22.524 --> 00:00:24.224
Well. technically
I'm a no-rent PI.

11
00:00:27.327 --> 00:00:28.997
[♪ suspenseful music plays]

12
00:00:56.056 --> 00:00:57.391
[chattering on radio]

13
00:00:58.492 --> 00:01:00.227
[parent 1]
None of the neighbors
saw anything?

14
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:03.531
2:00 a.m.
You're lucky the car alarm
woke you before it melted.

15
00:01:04.164 --> 00:01:07.569
Molly wanted to get one
of those doorbell cameras
last Christmas.

16
00:01:07.702 --> 00:01:09.102
Might have been a good idea.

17
00:01:09.904 --> 00:01:11.739
You sure you don't know
what this is all about?

18
00:01:15.375 --> 00:01:16.978
I'm sorry. we have no idea.

19
00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:22.115
[♪ upbeat music plays]

20
00:01:22.249 --> 00:01:24.686
What do you mean.
your house rolled
into a sinkhole?

21
00:01:24.819 --> 00:01:29.791
Uh. well. Officer Penmar.
I mean exactly that. I was
actually home at the time.

22
00:01:30.592 --> 00:01:33.861
If you've ever wondered
what the spin cycle
feels like. it hurts.

23
00:01:33.995 --> 00:01:36.731
Well. under "reason for
parolee's change of address."

24
00:01:36.864 --> 00:01:39.199
we'll just write "act of God."

25
00:01:39.333 --> 00:01:43.071
Yes. Oh.
my new address for now.

26
00:01:45.172 --> 00:01:48.076
-This is
your ex-wife's place. right?
-Mm-hmm. her and her wife's.

27
00:01:48.843 --> 00:01:53.380
-"Detective Mel Abreu.
FLPD." A cop?
-[smacks lips] Yep.

28
00:01:53.514 --> 00:01:56.249
-And Sofia. age 11. is...
-Mel's daughter.

29
00:01:56.751 --> 00:01:58.452
Y'all need to go
on <i>Family Feud.</i>

30
00:01:59.386 --> 00:02:02.790
Okay. So. they excited
to meet me tomorrow night?

31
00:02:03.357 --> 00:02:06.293
I mean. who wouldn't be excited
to meet their houseguest's
parole officer?

32
00:02:06.426 --> 00:02:09.897
Well. here in Florida.
it is "conditional
release officer."

33
00:02:10.031 --> 00:02:11.398
-Right.
-And you're the one

34
00:02:11.532 --> 00:02:13.300
-who decided to change
their address.
-That's true.

35
00:02:13.433 --> 00:02:15.737
A home visit is just procedure.

36
00:02:16.504 --> 00:02:18.773
Hey. you! Off of the dolphin!

37
00:02:18.906 --> 00:02:21.643
This is a golf course.
not a jungle gym!

38
00:02:22.175 --> 00:02:24.112
So this place. it's. uh...

39
00:02:24.646 --> 00:02:25.847
it's all yours now. huh?

40
00:02:25.980 --> 00:02:28.916
[sighs] Yeah. Divorce is final
as of a week ago.

41
00:02:29.050 --> 00:02:31.786
-He got the boat.
and I got this headache.
-[laughs]

42
00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:33.453
So. how's
your side hustle going?

43
00:02:33.588 --> 00:02:36.691
Well. Decker Investigations
is not a hustle.
side or otherwise.

44
00:02:36.824 --> 00:02:39.027
I even got a website.

45
00:02:39.159 --> 00:02:40.394
Take a look.

46
00:02:41.062 --> 00:02:42.664
[exhales]

47
00:02:42.797 --> 00:02:47.502
"Covert surveillance."
"asset recovery." and "wrongful
death investigations."

48
00:02:47.635 --> 00:02:49.837
[sighs] This is where
I remind you

49
00:02:49.971 --> 00:02:52.472
that you're required to
avoid contact with criminals.

50
00:02:52.607 --> 00:02:55.375
If you don't keep
your nose clean. you're going
right back to Apalachee.

51
00:02:55.510 --> 00:02:57.645
Cleanest in Fort Laud.
I promise.

52
00:02:58.913 --> 00:03:01.314
Are you sure
it wouldn't be easier
if I just gave you a job here?

53
00:03:01.448 --> 00:03:03.985
You could be. I don't know.
my snow-cone guy.

54
00:03:04.118 --> 00:03:05.485
That is tempting.

55
00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:07.555
Actually. I'm supposed to meet
some clients in 30 minutes.

56
00:03:07.689 --> 00:03:09.824
-so if we're done here...
-Yeah.

57
00:03:10.525 --> 00:03:11.759
Thank you.

58
00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:14.862
-Uh. R.J.!
-Yeah?

59
00:03:14.996 --> 00:03:16.164
Behave yourself.

60
00:03:17.765 --> 00:03:19.499
[♪ "Thanks to You" playing]

61
00:03:19.634 --> 00:03:26.574
♪ <i>Thanks to you</i>
<i>I feel like a man</i>
<i>Without any plan...</i> ♪

62
00:03:26.708 --> 00:03:32.780
[exhales] Uh. okay.
Bryce. Molly. forgive me.
but "you can't hide" from who?

63
00:03:32.914 --> 00:03:35.817
From Goose.
We're pretty sure it was Goose.

64
00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:38.720
This guy I dated
a few times years ago.

65
00:03:38.853 --> 00:03:40.353
His real name is Jared Tapp.

66
00:03:40.487 --> 00:03:43.157
Everyone just called him Goose
'cause he loved <i>Top Gun</i>
so much.

67
00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:45.059
-He was also a big fan of meth.
-Ah.

68
00:03:45.526 --> 00:03:47.962
But it was a long time ago.
It's not your fault.

69
00:03:48.096 --> 00:03:51.398
Uh. yeah.
Goose has been in and out
of prison. in and out of rehab.

70
00:03:51.532 --> 00:03:53.801
Every couple of years.
he shows up wanting something.

71
00:03:53.935 --> 00:03:54.969
Hmm.

72
00:03:55.703 --> 00:03:59.272
The other night
after the cops left. back
in the house. I found this.

73
00:04:05.513 --> 00:04:07.715
[R.J.] "Your past
is coming back to haunt you.

74
00:04:07.849 --> 00:04:11.986
10K under the green bench
at Loggerhead Park
tomorrow by noon.

75
00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:13.788
Or next time
I light up your house."

76
00:04:15.723 --> 00:04:18.559
And the reason
you didn't wanna take this
to the police is...

77
00:04:18.693 --> 00:04:20.695
Goose has a cousin who's a cop.

78
00:04:20.828 --> 00:04:24.599
He's made things go away
for Goose before.

79
00:04:24.732 --> 00:04:26.266
We were afraid
if we told them...

80
00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:28.268
Yeah. no. I get it.
I get it. I get it.

81
00:04:28.401 --> 00:04:31.271
Um. and I think I-I know what
to do. [inhales sharply]

82
00:04:31.404 --> 00:04:33.273
Can you get
the 10K together before noon?

83
00:04:33.406 --> 00:04:37.145
Yeah. but the whole reason
we came to you was
so we wouldn't...

84
00:04:37.277 --> 00:04:40.982
No. I... I'm not recommending
you pay him. Well. I am.
But only temporarily.

85
00:04:41.115 --> 00:04:42.550
I'm gonna put the money
under the bench.

86
00:04:42.683 --> 00:04:45.153
and then I'll watch
from a distance
until he comes for it.

87
00:04:45.285 --> 00:04:47.054
I'll take pictures
we can take to the police.

88
00:04:48.388 --> 00:04:52.260
It won't matter
who Goose's cousin is if
we have photographic evidence.

89
00:04:54.361 --> 00:04:55.863
That sound like a plan?

90
00:04:56.496 --> 00:04:58.465
[camera shutter clicking]

91
00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:04.138
Ugh. You know.
this is like finding out
about Santa Claus.

92
00:05:04.272 --> 00:05:07.775
-It's devastating. honestly.
-[R.J.] What are
you talking about?

93
00:05:08.976 --> 00:05:11.879
Learning your job
is this boring hurts my soul.

94
00:05:12.013 --> 00:05:13.948
Well. I didn't invite you.
remember? You asked to come.

95
00:05:14.081 --> 00:05:16.951
Yeah. 'cause I assumed that
a stakeout would be awesome.

96
00:05:17.084 --> 00:05:20.288
-not a damn.
I don't know. sleep aid.
-[chuckles]

97
00:05:22.924 --> 00:05:24.859
How'd it go
with your CRO today?

98
00:05:26.627 --> 00:05:29.597
Still not such a fan
of the whole. uh. PI thing.

99
00:05:31.132 --> 00:05:33.366
She offered me a job
making snow cones.

100
00:05:36.304 --> 00:05:38.072
Benefits?

101
00:05:38.206 --> 00:05:41.542
[stammers] You tell me
it's not more exciting than
what we're doing right now.

102
00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:43.511
[chuckling] Come on.

103
00:05:46.781 --> 00:05:48.783
-You got eyes on the target?
-[R.J.] Yeah.
it could be Goose.

104
00:05:48.916 --> 00:05:50.483
He's headed straight
for the money.

105
00:05:50.618 --> 00:05:52.385
-What. the guy
in the dorky hat?
-Yep.

106
00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:53.988
What is that.
a bandage on his hand?

107
00:05:54.121 --> 00:05:56.557
Yeah. could be
from that flamethrower
you mentioned.

108
00:05:56.691 --> 00:05:57.859
Hey. wait. Where you going?

109
00:05:57.992 --> 00:05:59.861
I don't have his face.
I need a better look.

110
00:05:59.994 --> 00:06:01.796
-Hey--
-Stay here. watch the car.

111
00:06:01.929 --> 00:06:03.231
[stammers]

112
00:06:13.975 --> 00:06:15.176
Damn it.

113
00:06:18.411 --> 00:06:20.480
[horns honking]

114
00:06:20.982 --> 00:06:22.583
[tires screeching]

115
00:06:22.717 --> 00:06:24.018
[driver shouts]

116
00:06:34.762 --> 00:06:36.197
No!

117
00:06:37.665 --> 00:06:39.867
Man. what the hell
is wrong with you?

118
00:06:40.701 --> 00:06:42.435
It's okay. Officer. I'm okay.

119
00:06:43.371 --> 00:06:45.306
All right. roll over.
show me your wrists.

120
00:06:45.907 --> 00:06:47.208
Are you serious?

121
00:06:47.341 --> 00:06:48.943
Come on. Let's go.

122
00:06:49.543 --> 00:06:50.745
[sighs]

123
00:06:50.878 --> 00:06:51.913
Nice.

124
00:06:52.046 --> 00:06:53.080
Damn.

125
00:06:59.754 --> 00:07:00.788
Thanks. Bye.

126
00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:06.394
Say "never."

127
00:07:07.328 --> 00:07:08.329
Uh...

128
00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:09.997
-Never.
-Again.

129
00:07:10.131 --> 00:07:12.199
[scoffs] Never.

130
00:07:12.333 --> 00:07:14.869
-No. stupid. Say "never again."
-Right.

131
00:07:15.002 --> 00:07:16.504
-Uh. never again.
-Uh-huh.

132
00:07:17.238 --> 00:07:20.440
Uh. you know this is. like.
a terrible place to stab
someone. right?

133
00:07:20.574 --> 00:07:23.077
-You want the good news
first or the bad?
-[clears throat. groans]

134
00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:24.879
I take it the... [groans]

135
00:07:25.012 --> 00:07:27.715
...good news is that
the hot dog vendor's
not going to press charges?

136
00:07:27.848 --> 00:07:32.520
The bad is you're about to buy
him a new cart and all
the hot dogs you spilled.

137
00:07:32.653 --> 00:07:33.688
[R.J. sighs]

138
00:07:33.821 --> 00:07:36.857
-Done. And thank you.
-Mm-hmm.

139
00:07:37.391 --> 00:07:40.261
If you're looking for
missed calls from your CRO.
there shouldn't be any.

140
00:07:40.394 --> 00:07:43.831
This went into the system
as an incident report
and not an arrest.

141
00:07:43.965 --> 00:07:46.100
-She wasn't notified.
-Thank you.

142
00:07:46.233 --> 00:07:49.270
But it would make
an interesting story to tell

143
00:07:49.403 --> 00:07:51.038
at dinner tomorrow night.
don't you think?

144
00:07:51.172 --> 00:07:54.275
It would. but if you don't.
there might be 100 hot dogs
in it for you.

145
00:07:54.408 --> 00:07:55.710
[chuckles]

146
00:07:55.843 --> 00:07:57.178
-Get out.
-Okay.

147
00:07:57.745 --> 00:07:59.547
[R.J.]
What about this one here?
A little less blurry?

148
00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:00.681
[Molly sighs]

149
00:08:00.815 --> 00:08:02.350
I don't know. If it is Goose.

150
00:08:02.482 --> 00:08:04.652
-he's a little thicker
these days.
-[sighs] Yeah.

151
00:08:04.785 --> 00:08:07.388
Then again. his weight was
always kind of yo-yoing
up and down.

152
00:08:07.855 --> 00:08:10.091
You know. when money's tight.
less meth. more carbs.

153
00:08:10.224 --> 00:08:11.225
[chuckles]

154
00:08:12.126 --> 00:08:14.128
Is that something on his hand.
or is that. like. a smudge?

155
00:08:14.261 --> 00:08:17.631
Nah. it's a Band-Aid.
It's really the only
identifiable feature I got.

156
00:08:17.765 --> 00:08:20.868
I'm sorry. But if you want.
we can still take it
to the police.

157
00:08:21.002 --> 00:08:24.071
-We can share your suspicions.
-No. No. that's okay.

158
00:08:24.205 --> 00:08:26.140
If I know Goose.
this is over now.

159
00:08:26.273 --> 00:08:28.843
I don't want to put Bryce
through any more craziness.

160
00:08:29.844 --> 00:08:32.279
[smacks lips] Yesterday.
you made it sound like
you and Goose.

161
00:08:32.413 --> 00:08:33.681
you weren't all that serious.

162
00:08:33.814 --> 00:08:37.485
Yeah. I try to give people
that impression.

163
00:08:37.618 --> 00:08:38.886
especially in front
of my husband.

164
00:08:39.487 --> 00:08:41.188
You two had
a real history. huh?

165
00:08:41.322 --> 00:08:42.757
We were a thing
for over a year.

166
00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:45.393
This was before
he put the "career"
in "career criminal."

167
00:08:46.293 --> 00:08:50.765
But Bryce doesn't
know it was serious.
so if you could not mention...

168
00:08:51.799 --> 00:08:54.168
Thing is. I feel responsible
for the money you lost.

169
00:08:54.301 --> 00:08:55.469
[Molly chuckles]

170
00:08:55.603 --> 00:08:58.072
If you'll let me.
I'd like to try to get it back.

171
00:08:58.639 --> 00:09:00.908
-How?
-You know where he lives?

172
00:09:01.709 --> 00:09:03.344
Any old friends still in touch?

173
00:09:04.111 --> 00:09:06.547
I mean. I may have
a few old numbers somewhere.

174
00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:09.316
A couple buddies of his.
an aunt. an uncle.

175
00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:12.720
But I'd be surprised
if he's still on speaking terms
with any of them.

176
00:09:12.853 --> 00:09:15.524
Send them to me.
I'll see if I can get
a bead on him.

177
00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:17.324
[chuckles]

178
00:09:17.458 --> 00:09:18.893
-What?
-I learned my lesson. you know.

179
00:09:19.026 --> 00:09:20.895
I really didn't need
another reminder

180
00:09:21.028 --> 00:09:23.631
that I made a huge mistake
a long time ago.

181
00:09:25.232 --> 00:09:28.335
You ever have
five minutes of your life
you'd do anything to have back?

182
00:09:28.869 --> 00:09:31.405
-I know exactly
what that's like.
-[chuckles]

183
00:09:35.242 --> 00:09:37.978
Yeah. that's right.
Miss Picquand.
It was your nephew's car I hit.

184
00:09:38.112 --> 00:09:41.048
I was towing
this Nissan Z. Repo job...

185
00:09:41.182 --> 00:09:44.118
Well. it don't matter.
But there was this dog. eh?

186
00:09:44.251 --> 00:09:46.287
I up and swerved and...
[blows raspberry]

187
00:09:47.054 --> 00:09:48.222
No. ma'am. No. no. no. ma'am.

188
00:09:48.355 --> 00:09:51.125
No. I won't feel right
till I get a check in his hand.

189
00:09:51.258 --> 00:09:54.261
-$1.400.
-[whispering] Hey.
Just one more? Yeah?

190
00:09:54.395 --> 00:09:57.566
[whispering]
Okay. try to limit yourself
to 40 or 50. please. Thank you.

191
00:09:58.499 --> 00:10:01.068
You say he's
there most afternoons.
do you? All right. [chuckles]

192
00:10:01.202 --> 00:10:05.372
Yes. ma'am. Yes. ma'am.
I'll send him your love.
Absolutely.

193
00:10:05.507 --> 00:10:07.608
That was Remy Tremblay.

194
00:10:08.876 --> 00:10:11.979
Big old tub from Cell Block D.
used to take my pudding cup
at lunch.

195
00:10:12.113 --> 00:10:15.249
What are you talking about?
That was my client's
ex-boyfriend's aunt.

196
00:10:15.382 --> 00:10:17.618
[sighs] No. the voice
you were doing.

197
00:10:19.588 --> 00:10:22.623
Remy.
[imitating Remy] Wish. eh?

198
00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:26.193
-I wish you'd give me
that pudding.
-Chills. [chuckles]

199
00:10:26.327 --> 00:10:28.896
-Yeah.
-The aunt tell you
where to find Goose?

200
00:10:29.029 --> 00:10:31.699
Yeah. he's staying with a buddy
at the Las Olas trailer parks.

201
00:10:31.832 --> 00:10:34.802
This time of day.
he's pretty deep
into a six-pack or three.

202
00:10:34.935 --> 00:10:36.737
All right. So what's the plan?

203
00:10:36.871 --> 00:10:39.440
You go over there
and ask him nicely for 10K?

204
00:10:39.574 --> 00:10:41.475
Nicely. not so nicely.

205
00:10:41.610 --> 00:10:43.110
I guess it depends
how drunk he is.

206
00:10:51.553 --> 00:10:54.556
There he is.
Looks like I'm just in time.

207
00:10:55.189 --> 00:10:56.690
I know you?

208
00:10:56.824 --> 00:11:00.961
Yep. I'm the ghost
of beer future.
I'm here from the year 2034.

209
00:11:01.563 --> 00:11:04.331
Huh? No? You don't recognize me
from this morning?

210
00:11:04.465 --> 00:11:06.500
The hot dogs. the running.

211
00:11:06.635 --> 00:11:09.136
You know what? Forget it.
The sixer is a peace offering.

212
00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:12.541
You give me the ten grand.
I give you the beer.
No one calls the cops.

213
00:11:12.673 --> 00:11:14.842
-We both go home happy.
What do you say?
-Ten grand?

214
00:11:14.975 --> 00:11:18.647
Yeah. Goose. ten grand.
Ten grand. You give it to me
or you give it to the cops.

215
00:11:18.779 --> 00:11:20.247
-That's up to you.
-You know what?

216
00:11:20.381 --> 00:11:22.617
How about instead
I just kick your ass?

217
00:11:24.685 --> 00:11:26.754
Whoa! Whoa.

218
00:11:26.887 --> 00:11:28.189
You have a prosthetic foot?

219
00:11:28.322 --> 00:11:29.558
-Yeah.
-Since when? [sighs]

220
00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:31.025
I don't know. a year ago.

221
00:11:31.158 --> 00:11:33.194
I flipped my ATV
when I was out in Punta Gorda.

222
00:11:33.327 --> 00:11:34.962
Are we gonna fight or not?

223
00:11:35.095 --> 00:11:37.498
Not. Because
I don't think you beat me
in a foot race this morning.

224
00:11:37.632 --> 00:11:39.900
-Are you making fun of me?
-No. I'm not making fun of you.

225
00:11:40.034 --> 00:11:41.468
But you're not getting
my beer either.

226
00:11:42.537 --> 00:11:44.205
Probably gonna need it
more than you anyway.

227
00:11:44.338 --> 00:11:45.839
Hey!

228
00:11:45.973 --> 00:11:49.611
All right. in position.
In position. Let's go.
Let's go. let's go.

229
00:11:50.244 --> 00:11:51.546
Denny. second. Hayden!

230
00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:54.815
Move your butt.
You're playing third.
Slide over.

231
00:11:54.949 --> 00:11:56.183
Good. You got this.

232
00:11:56.317 --> 00:11:58.553
Vince. lighten it up.
Let's get the good vibes going.

233
00:11:59.453 --> 00:12:01.656
[Vince] All right. turn two.

234
00:12:01.789 --> 00:12:02.923
This one's coming
to you. Hayden.

235
00:12:03.057 --> 00:12:04.526
There it is.

236
00:12:04.659 --> 00:12:06.360
-Okay. boys. Let's go.
-[phone ringing]

237
00:12:08.229 --> 00:12:11.031
-Mr. Decker. Hi.
-Hi. Uh...

238
00:12:11.566 --> 00:12:13.033
Is now a good time
for an update?

239
00:12:13.167 --> 00:12:16.203
Yeah. we're at
Henry's baseball game.
But it's fine. I just sat down.

240
00:12:16.337 --> 00:12:21.075
So the person who made off
with your money this morning
wasn't Goose.

241
00:12:21.208 --> 00:12:23.744
What? Are you sure?

242
00:12:23.877 --> 00:12:25.246
<i>Wish I weren't.</i> [sighs]

243
00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:27.716
I don't understand.
If it wasn't him...

244
00:12:27.848 --> 00:12:30.150
We should talk. I-I wanna know
if there's anyone else that--

245
00:12:30.284 --> 00:12:31.318
[Henry] <i>Dad!</i>

246
00:12:31.452 --> 00:12:33.454
-Dad! Dad!
-What's the matter?

247
00:12:34.054 --> 00:12:35.222
Henry?

248
00:12:35.356 --> 00:12:37.559
Molly. what's going on?
What is it? What's wrong?

249
00:12:38.125 --> 00:12:39.126
You okay?

250
00:12:41.996 --> 00:12:44.566
I picked up my glove.
and all that fell out.

251
00:12:47.901 --> 00:12:51.105
"You made me run. Your turn."

252
00:12:57.177 --> 00:12:58.812
[crickets chirping]

253
00:12:58.946 --> 00:13:01.815
Brooks. why don't
we show Henry where
he's gonna be sleeping tonight.

254
00:13:02.816 --> 00:13:04.918
-Thanks. Vince.
-You got it. buddy.

255
00:13:08.657 --> 00:13:10.958
You're positive
this wasn't Goose?

256
00:13:11.559 --> 00:13:14.962
Even if he had both of
his feet. he was three sheets
to the wind when I left him.

257
00:13:15.095 --> 00:13:16.631
There's no way
he could have gotten in

258
00:13:16.765 --> 00:13:18.633
and out of that dugout
without someone noticing.

259
00:13:18.767 --> 00:13:20.401
None of this
is making any sense.

260
00:13:20.535 --> 00:13:24.338
The note we got
at the house said our past
was coming back to haunt us.

261
00:13:24.471 --> 00:13:25.839
But if it wasn't Goose...

262
00:13:26.473 --> 00:13:28.610
Well. look. first things first.

263
00:13:28.743 --> 00:13:31.211
Do you feel safe here?
At least for tonight?

264
00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:34.114
Yeah. we've known
Vince and his wife
for years. And...

265
00:13:34.248 --> 00:13:37.117
And Henry and Brooks were
on the same all-star teams.

266
00:13:37.652 --> 00:13:40.187
And I can't think of a reason
that the person
who's doing this

267
00:13:40.321 --> 00:13:41.723
would think
to look for us here.

268
00:13:41.855 --> 00:13:44.024
Okay. [inhales sharply]

269
00:13:44.793 --> 00:13:48.095
Well. good news.
Whoever he is. I think
he may have screwed up tonight.

270
00:13:48.663 --> 00:13:49.664
You see this?

271
00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:52.801
I'm hoping that's blood.
The guy I chased today.

272
00:13:52.933 --> 00:13:54.569
he had a bandage on his hand.

273
00:13:54.703 --> 00:13:57.004
Maybe when he put
the bullets in. he left
a little of himself behind.

274
00:13:57.137 --> 00:14:00.675
Now. obviously
I-I can't run DNA. but if we
did take it to the police--

275
00:14:00.809 --> 00:14:02.976
I told you the other day
w-we're not going
to the police.

276
00:14:03.110 --> 00:14:05.379
Right. but that was
because of Goose's cousin.

277
00:14:05.513 --> 00:14:06.847
And now that we know
Goose isn't our guy--

278
00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:09.149
-Well. do we?
-Sweetie. he just told us.

279
00:14:09.283 --> 00:14:11.051
We know that the guy
that he was chasing
wasn't Goose.

280
00:14:11.185 --> 00:14:12.252
but maybe that was
Goose's cousin.

281
00:14:12.386 --> 00:14:14.288
Maybe they're working together.
What then?

282
00:14:14.421 --> 00:14:17.091
Well. Goose isn't
the only one with friends
in the police department.

283
00:14:17.224 --> 00:14:18.526
If you want.
I can introduce you to--

284
00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:19.828
No!

285
00:14:20.894 --> 00:14:22.996
We did everything you told us
to do this morning. Everything.

286
00:14:23.130 --> 00:14:24.231
And what happened?

287
00:14:24.365 --> 00:14:26.100
The guy who did this
spotted you.

288
00:14:26.233 --> 00:14:28.969
And now $10.000 isn't enough.
he wants us to leave town too.

289
00:14:29.103 --> 00:14:31.238
The message didn't say
leave town. it said run.

290
00:14:31.372 --> 00:14:33.742
-Is there a difference?
-It's okay. He's right.

291
00:14:34.908 --> 00:14:36.110
Today did not go as planned.

292
00:14:36.944 --> 00:14:38.513
I'm sorry. I really am.

293
00:14:39.179 --> 00:14:42.550
So I'm hoping you guys will
let me stay on and work for you
free of charge.

294
00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:45.152
At least until you two
and Henry feel safe.

295
00:14:45.285 --> 00:14:46.521
We would appreciate that.

296
00:14:47.221 --> 00:14:50.692
Is there anyone else
you can think of that would
put you through all this?

297
00:14:50.825 --> 00:14:54.261
[sighs] I mean.
I teach kindergarten.
and he does people's taxes.

298
00:14:54.395 --> 00:14:57.197
We're the family that gives out
king-size candy bars
at Halloween.

299
00:14:57.331 --> 00:14:58.600
I thought everyone liked us.

300
00:14:58.733 --> 00:15:00.167
What about one of your clients?

301
00:15:01.201 --> 00:15:03.070
Anyone ever get really angry
when they found out

302
00:15:03.203 --> 00:15:04.873
how much they owed
the government?

303
00:15:05.372 --> 00:15:06.473
No one comes to mind.

304
00:15:06.608 --> 00:15:09.778
But my partner's more
the face of the company.

305
00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:11.912
so if someone had a problem.
they'd go to him.

306
00:15:18.485 --> 00:15:19.754
Are you kidding? It's a dump.

307
00:15:19.888 --> 00:15:23.223
I believe the listing calls it
"a fixer-upper's dream."

308
00:15:23.357 --> 00:15:25.392
We can't show this to R.J.
It's worse than his old place.

309
00:15:25.527 --> 00:15:27.161
and his old place is
upside down in a crater.

310
00:15:27.294 --> 00:15:29.329
You are aware
of the man's budget. yes?

311
00:15:29.463 --> 00:15:33.033
He is paying us
rent in babysitting
and day-old hot dogs.

312
00:15:33.167 --> 00:15:35.002
This sudden interest
in rehousing R.J..

313
00:15:35.135 --> 00:15:37.271
it wouldn't have
anything to do with
the dinner we're hosting

314
00:15:37.404 --> 00:15:39.406
for his conditional release
officer tonight. would it?

315
00:15:39.541 --> 00:15:43.944
It wouldn't not have
anything to do with it. No.

316
00:15:44.077 --> 00:15:47.816
"Sofia. meet the nice lady
who collects Uncle R.J.'s pee
every few weeks

317
00:15:47.948 --> 00:15:50.484
-to make sure
he isn't doing drugs."
-Sweetie...

318
00:15:50.618 --> 00:15:52.620
He was supposed to be here
one week. okay?

319
00:15:52.754 --> 00:15:56.256
And yes. he's a good guy.
He means well.

320
00:15:56.390 --> 00:15:58.992
I get it. <i>Pero</i> he's also...
[inhales sharply]

321
00:15:59.761 --> 00:16:00.762
-[sighs]
-What?

322
00:16:00.895 --> 00:16:02.496
A crap magnet.

323
00:16:02.630 --> 00:16:04.766
He attracts trouble.
Trouble attracts him.

324
00:16:04.899 --> 00:16:07.869
It's only a matter of time
before he tracks
some right in here.

325
00:16:08.001 --> 00:16:09.303
[exclaims]

326
00:16:10.939 --> 00:16:12.774
He hasn't always been that way.

327
00:16:14.141 --> 00:16:16.611
Not when we were
buddies at the <i>Herald.</i>
Not when we were married.

328
00:16:16.744 --> 00:16:18.913
I mean. he took chances.
Most photographers do.

329
00:16:19.046 --> 00:16:21.616
But he always knew
where the lines were. He didn't
go looking for trouble.

330
00:16:21.749 --> 00:16:23.718
I didn't say
he goes looking for trouble.

331
00:16:23.852 --> 00:16:25.753
-You said he finds it.
-Mm-hmm.

332
00:16:25.887 --> 00:16:27.120
And you're right.

333
00:16:27.254 --> 00:16:29.990
The thing is. I worry sometimes
it's a little my fault.

334
00:16:30.123 --> 00:16:31.726
How?

335
00:16:31.860 --> 00:16:34.161
When we separated.
the problem wasn't that
we didn't love each other.

336
00:16:34.294 --> 00:16:36.163
it's that we were only
ever supposed to be pals.

337
00:16:36.296 --> 00:16:38.165
And so afterwards.
we stayed pals.

338
00:16:38.298 --> 00:16:42.804
But then once you and I got
together. I pulled back
a little. and then a lot.

339
00:16:43.972 --> 00:16:47.809
I mean. me and my ex
getting beers. watching
the Marlins twice a week.

340
00:16:47.942 --> 00:16:49.878
sort of a lot to explain
to my sexy new girlfriend.

341
00:16:50.845 --> 00:16:52.881
But because I pulled back. I...

342
00:16:53.013 --> 00:16:55.650
I wasn't there
when things fell apart.

343
00:16:55.783 --> 00:16:59.921
So really. if we think
about it. it's my fault
he went to prison.

344
00:17:00.053 --> 00:17:01.856
Okay. beating up that guy
who broke into his car.

345
00:17:01.990 --> 00:17:04.659
-that isn't anybody's
fault but his.
-Mm-hmm.

346
00:17:04.792 --> 00:17:06.961
But it took him
a while to get to that place.

347
00:17:07.094 --> 00:17:09.496
And I guess I wish
I'd been paying
better attention.

348
00:17:10.230 --> 00:17:12.000
-[sighs]
-Babe.

349
00:17:12.132 --> 00:17:15.335
I am not asking
to adopt him. I promise.

350
00:17:15.469 --> 00:17:17.772
I just want to be more
there for him this time.

351
00:17:18.940 --> 00:17:21.241
You'll still show him
the fixer-upper's dream?

352
00:17:23.176 --> 00:17:24.177
Yeah.

353
00:17:24.311 --> 00:17:26.881
[sighs] Okay.

354
00:17:29.049 --> 00:17:31.218
[inhales sharply] Hmm.

355
00:17:40.093 --> 00:17:42.864
Wow. You went
full mystery wall.

356
00:17:43.865 --> 00:17:46.466
Gotta be honest. I don't know
why they do that in the movies.

357
00:17:47.167 --> 00:17:50.538
It's depressing. looking at
everything you don't know.

358
00:17:52.072 --> 00:17:53.775
Did you sleep last night?

359
00:17:55.677 --> 00:17:57.779
[sighs] I just... I need
some more time.

360
00:17:57.912 --> 00:18:02.149
But the dad. Bryce. he...
he came apart last night.

361
00:18:02.282 --> 00:18:06.286
I was walking him out.
he started talking about moving
his family to Santa Clara.

362
00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:07.789
where he went to grad school.

363
00:18:08.856 --> 00:18:10.892
Well. I can think of worse
places to start over.

364
00:18:11.025 --> 00:18:12.392
Yeah. I know.
but why should they?

365
00:18:12.527 --> 00:18:16.064
Oh. I don't know. A maniac with
a grudge and a flamethrower?

366
00:18:17.732 --> 00:18:19.266
I gotta go meet
his business partner.

367
00:18:19.399 --> 00:18:22.036
See if he can think
of anyone with a grudge
and a flamethrower.

368
00:18:23.504 --> 00:18:24.906
What's up? You need something?

369
00:18:26.908 --> 00:18:28.943
Just want to make sure
that you're still on for dinner

370
00:18:29.077 --> 00:18:30.645
with your special friend
tonight?

371
00:18:30.778 --> 00:18:32.046
Oh. yeah. I wouldn't miss it.

372
00:18:32.179 --> 00:18:34.281
I mean. not without getting
violated back to prison.

373
00:18:34.414 --> 00:18:36.216
[Catherine chuckles]

374
00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:39.754
Gosh. Mr. Decker. I'm at
a loss. We like the people
we work for. and they like us.

375
00:18:39.887 --> 00:18:41.956
Hard to imagine anyone
going after Bryce.

376
00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:44.626
And you're sure
you can't think of anyone
who might have gotten ticked

377
00:18:44.759 --> 00:18:47.260
when they owed Uncle Sam
more than they were expecting?

378
00:18:47.394 --> 00:18:50.230
Well. sure. but nobody
who ever shot the messenger

379
00:18:50.364 --> 00:18:51.733
or "flamethrower-ed" him.
you know.

380
00:18:51.866 --> 00:18:53.768
You don't have any idea when
he'll be back to work. do you?

381
00:18:53.901 --> 00:18:55.570
[chuckles] I'm sorry. I don't.

382
00:18:55.703 --> 00:18:58.640
[sucks teeth] Well. save him.
okay? I-I love the guy.

383
00:18:59.107 --> 00:19:01.375
And if I'm being honest.
I'm screwed if he doesn't
come back soon.

384
00:19:01.509 --> 00:19:03.477
He's the one who keeps
this place humming.

385
00:19:03.611 --> 00:19:05.613
He does. huh? Hmm.

386
00:19:06.246 --> 00:19:08.816
That's funny.
I noticed it was just
your name on the door.

387
00:19:08.950 --> 00:19:12.352
and the sign.
and the letterhead.
the ads. everything.

388
00:19:12.486 --> 00:19:15.188
If I had a nickel
for every time I offered
to make him partner...

389
00:19:15.322 --> 00:19:16.891
He always just says
he doesn't need the credit.

390
00:19:17.025 --> 00:19:19.794
Plus. you know.
he'd have to be certified.

391
00:19:21.395 --> 00:19:22.429
[smacks lips]

392
00:19:23.263 --> 00:19:25.767
Sorry. are you saying
Bryce isn't a CPA?

393
00:19:26.433 --> 00:19:27.467
Really?

394
00:19:29.169 --> 00:19:31.706
Last night. he told me he went
to grad school in Santa Clara.

395
00:19:31.839 --> 00:19:33.007
-Did he?
-Yeah.

396
00:19:33.141 --> 00:19:34.108
Huh.

397
00:19:34.241 --> 00:19:35.576
Maybe he just never sat
for the exam?

398
00:19:35.710 --> 00:19:37.979
Maybe. But if he's
as good as you say he is.

399
00:19:38.112 --> 00:19:40.715
then why would
he go to grad school
without getting certified?

400
00:19:41.448 --> 00:19:43.618
He really never mentioned
Santa Clara to you?

401
00:19:43.751 --> 00:19:44.752
Sorry. no.

402
00:19:45.452 --> 00:19:47.655
Uh. but you know us
number crunchers.

403
00:19:47.789 --> 00:19:49.924
Not always great
at the interpersonal stuff.

404
00:19:52.994 --> 00:19:55.530
[Wish humming "In the Hall
of the Mountain King"]

405
00:20:00.535 --> 00:20:03.538
All right. use the legs.
Use the legs. [groans]

406
00:20:04.972 --> 00:20:06.507
All right. [clears throat]

407
00:20:07.175 --> 00:20:08.341
[yelps]

408
00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:10.745
You about scared
the bejesus out of me.

409
00:20:10.878 --> 00:20:13.413
I'm sorry. I-I needed
a quiet place to work.

410
00:20:13.548 --> 00:20:15.315
-I'm sorry.
-You're fine.

411
00:20:16.751 --> 00:20:17.952
[exhales]

412
00:20:18.886 --> 00:20:20.220
Something got you in a state.

413
00:20:21.155 --> 00:20:24.759
Last night.
Bryce Danner told me he went
to grad school in Santa Clara.

414
00:20:24.892 --> 00:20:26.828
but I searched
every school in the area.

415
00:20:26.961 --> 00:20:29.764
There's no record of anyone
with that name.

416
00:20:29.897 --> 00:20:33.634
Yeah. well. there's probably
no record of me attending
Iron Tiger Tae Kwon Do.

417
00:20:33.768 --> 00:20:35.235
but I did take six classes.

418
00:20:35.368 --> 00:20:36.771
Broke a board and everything.

419
00:20:36.904 --> 00:20:40.074
There were graduating notices
for a Bryce Cartman.

420
00:20:40.208 --> 00:20:42.844
a Bryce Wachtel.
and a Bryce Hempstead.

421
00:20:43.376 --> 00:20:45.213
So I thought there
might be some clerical error.

422
00:20:45.345 --> 00:20:47.481
Searched those names.
I found this. Come here.

423
00:20:50.450 --> 00:20:51.586
What you got?

424
00:20:53.955 --> 00:21:00.595
Uh. Bryce Wachtel.
stabbed in San Francisco. 2011.

425
00:21:00.728 --> 00:21:01.763
Nearly died.

426
00:21:01.896 --> 00:21:03.330
Yeah. police never
found the perp.

427
00:21:03.463 --> 00:21:05.800
They suspected it was due
to a business dispute

428
00:21:05.933 --> 00:21:08.169
between Bryce Wachtel's
business partner

429
00:21:09.103 --> 00:21:10.571
and the Chinese Triad.

430
00:21:13.406 --> 00:21:17.310
Well. that's very interesting.
but I think you have to help
the Bryce you have

431
00:21:17.444 --> 00:21:18.946
before you move on
to another. no?

432
00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:20.615
No. that's the thing.

433
00:21:21.949 --> 00:21:23.316
They're the same guy.

434
00:21:23.885 --> 00:21:28.321
The last 15 years.
Bryce Wachtel has been living
under the name Bryce Danner.

435
00:21:29.924 --> 00:21:33.861
So he let you and his wife
think they were being
terrorized by an ex-boyfriend.

436
00:21:33.995 --> 00:21:36.931
but if I'm following. the more
likely scenario is his--

437
00:21:37.064 --> 00:21:39.934
It was someone who realized
he's on the run from the Triad.

438
00:21:52.780 --> 00:21:53.981
Well. say something.

439
00:21:55.149 --> 00:21:57.518
Can't believe I mentioned
Santa Clara last night.

440
00:21:58.820 --> 00:21:59.954
I'm sorry.

441
00:22:00.420 --> 00:22:02.757
I was scared.
I am scared. I just... I--

442
00:22:02.890 --> 00:22:04.659
Start from the beginning.
Tell me everything.

443
00:22:04.792 --> 00:22:07.460
Fifteen years ago.
I was living in San Francisco.

444
00:22:07.929 --> 00:22:11.398
I was doing tax work
with a partner. same as now.

445
00:22:12.667 --> 00:22:16.170
One of our clients was
this chain of car washes.

446
00:22:16.304 --> 00:22:19.307
They had an unusual
corporate structure.

447
00:22:19.439 --> 00:22:21.509
but they paid their bills.
paid their taxes.

448
00:22:21.642 --> 00:22:24.579
Bryce. they were a Triad
business. You were helping them
launder their money.

449
00:22:24.712 --> 00:22:26.379
They were laundering
their money.

450
00:22:26.514 --> 00:22:29.016
We had no idea we were
in bed with the Triads.

451
00:22:29.150 --> 00:22:32.854
I mean. we only ever met
the guy who. on paper.
owned the car washes.

452
00:22:33.888 --> 00:22:37.558
Then one day
this Triad gangster
shows up at the office.

453
00:22:37.692 --> 00:22:40.561
He's pissed off. He's...
He's accusing us of stealing
almost a million dollars.

454
00:22:40.695 --> 00:22:42.530
-Did you?
-No.

455
00:22:42.663 --> 00:22:45.465
But when we looked at it.
the business had a hole
in its books.

456
00:22:46.133 --> 00:22:49.003
That money was disappearing
into a shell company:

457
00:22:49.136 --> 00:22:50.705
Shadowblade Enterprises.

458
00:22:51.404 --> 00:22:53.040
Josh and I had
never even heard of it.

459
00:22:53.174 --> 00:22:55.543
And believe me.
a name that stupid.
we would have remembered.

460
00:22:55.676 --> 00:22:58.779
I take it the guy
that stabbed you.
he didn't believe you. right?

461
00:22:58.913 --> 00:23:03.317
I'm 99.9% sure the guy
who stabbed me was embezzling
the money himself.

462
00:23:03.885 --> 00:23:06.554
And I might have been able
to prove it if he hadn't
gotten himself killed

463
00:23:06.687 --> 00:23:09.223
in some gang war
before I got out
of the hospital.

464
00:23:10.258 --> 00:23:12.126
I was there for a while.

465
00:23:12.994 --> 00:23:15.263
-Liver transplant.
-Okay.

466
00:23:16.631 --> 00:23:18.900
And after I got out.
Josh and I went on the run.

467
00:23:19.033 --> 00:23:22.203
We moved out here.
helped each other
create new identities.

468
00:23:23.537 --> 00:23:25.873
I'm sorry. Josh lives
in the area too?

469
00:23:26.007 --> 00:23:27.440
Yeah.

470
00:23:27.575 --> 00:23:29.277
And obviously he knows
your real name
is Bryce Wachtel.

471
00:23:29.409 --> 00:23:31.913
Trust me. he is not
the one doing this to us.

472
00:23:32.046 --> 00:23:33.381
Would Molly agree?

473
00:23:35.249 --> 00:23:38.019
Molly doesn't.
um. know about any of this.

474
00:23:38.152 --> 00:23:41.155
She's never heard of
Josh or Bryce Wachtel.

475
00:23:41.289 --> 00:23:45.393
Look. when she and I first met.
I had only been here
for a couple of months.

476
00:23:45.526 --> 00:23:47.929
And I was worried
if I told her the truth.
I would lose her.

477
00:23:48.062 --> 00:23:51.532
Bryce. I understand not
wanting to scare her
back then. but now?

478
00:23:52.033 --> 00:23:55.403
Letting her think that the guy
that lit your car on fire
was her ex?

479
00:23:55.536 --> 00:23:56.837
I did think it was him...

480
00:23:57.405 --> 00:23:59.206
at first.

481
00:23:59.340 --> 00:24:02.977
But then last night. whoever
it is didn't just put bullets
in Henry's glove.

482
00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:05.413
There was a thumb drive too.

483
00:24:05.546 --> 00:24:07.615
<i>It had all</i>
<i>of my medical records</i>
<i>from San Francisco.</i>

484
00:24:07.748 --> 00:24:09.850
my surgery. my real name.
It was all there.

485
00:24:09.984 --> 00:24:11.819
All right. Who has access
to these records?

486
00:24:11.953 --> 00:24:14.021
Out here? Uh...

487
00:24:14.155 --> 00:24:18.125
My GP. I told him a long time
ago that the name change
was for business reasons.

488
00:24:18.259 --> 00:24:19.660
It didn't bump him.

489
00:24:20.127 --> 00:24:24.098
I have a copy at my office
and. uh... [inhales sharply]

490
00:24:24.231 --> 00:24:25.498
...and Josh has one.

491
00:24:25.633 --> 00:24:27.268
He was my emergency contact.

492
00:24:27.401 --> 00:24:29.469
It was in case anything
went wrong with the transplant.

493
00:24:29.603 --> 00:24:32.640
but I repeat.
he would never do this to us.

494
00:24:33.107 --> 00:24:35.409
Josh is in as much danger
from the Triad as I am.

495
00:24:37.545 --> 00:24:40.848
All right. two things:
You give me the thumb drive.

496
00:24:41.682 --> 00:24:43.284
You tell Molly the truth.

497
00:24:44.085 --> 00:24:46.787
I mean. she deserves
to know she has nothing
to do with this.

498
00:24:51.659 --> 00:24:52.693
Go ahead.

499
00:24:56.063 --> 00:24:59.467
No. Brooks. come on.
You got to step towards
your target. okay?

500
00:25:00.167 --> 00:25:01.836
Is it okay to go back
in there now?

501
00:25:04.972 --> 00:25:07.341
Uh. yeah. I'd give them
another minute.

502
00:25:10.411 --> 00:25:12.680
So this is everything that
you have on the thumb drive?

503
00:25:12.813 --> 00:25:15.049
Yeah. it's 22 pages
of Bryce's medical records.

504
00:25:15.182 --> 00:25:16.650
There you go.

505
00:25:16.784 --> 00:25:19.186
And this is helpful how?

506
00:25:20.154 --> 00:25:21.188
Page 16.

507
00:25:22.356 --> 00:25:23.791
[Catherine] Page 16.

508
00:25:25.626 --> 00:25:27.261
-What am I missing?
-Coffee ring.

509
00:25:27.395 --> 00:25:29.697
I mean.
maybe it was there whenever

510
00:25:29.830 --> 00:25:32.233
whoever left the thumb drive
scanned the original.

511
00:25:32.967 --> 00:25:35.236
So you go to Bryce's doctor
and his pal Josh

512
00:25:35.369 --> 00:25:38.539
and see which one has a copy
with a coffee ring
on the same page.

513
00:25:38.672 --> 00:25:40.141
I'm hoping. Yeah.

514
00:25:41.308 --> 00:25:44.278
Small detail.
Last time I checked.
PIs don't have subpoena power.

515
00:25:44.412 --> 00:25:46.280
so how are you gonna get
them to show you their copies?

516
00:25:46.414 --> 00:25:48.182
Wish is gonna help me with
the doctor tomorrow.

517
00:25:48.315 --> 00:25:52.521
but Josh. now living under
the name Sonny Tedesco.
is gonna be a bit trickier.

518
00:25:52.653 --> 00:25:55.756
Bryce didn't have
a current address.
so I gotta dig one up.

519
00:25:56.557 --> 00:25:57.658
[Mel] Hmm.

520
00:25:58.359 --> 00:25:59.528
-Mmm.
-Mom. check it out!

521
00:25:59.660 --> 00:26:00.928
-Mm-hmm?
-Uncle R.J. is teaching me

522
00:26:01.062 --> 00:26:02.096
how to make cheesecake.

523
00:26:02.229 --> 00:26:04.533
-Wow.
-He didn't even use a cookbook.

524
00:26:04.665 --> 00:26:07.735
Well. you know.
it sort of reminds me of this
famous prison recipe I know.

525
00:26:07.868 --> 00:26:09.538
It doesn't have to be baked
or refrigerated.

526
00:26:09.670 --> 00:26:12.239
so inmates can make it
using ingredients
they find in the canteen.

527
00:26:12.373 --> 00:26:13.908
I mean. cheesecake
is cheesecake. Am I right?

528
00:26:14.041 --> 00:26:15.276
-[doorbell rings]
-[R.J.] Oh.

529
00:26:15.409 --> 00:26:17.645
Ooh. Your date. I'll get it.

530
00:26:17.778 --> 00:26:19.647
Sofia. it's...
[chuckles] ...not my date.

531
00:26:19.780 --> 00:26:21.715
Not even close to my date.

532
00:26:23.684 --> 00:26:27.154
Amazing. And that's
when my father decided

533
00:26:27.288 --> 00:26:29.423
that R.J. got him
in the divorce.

534
00:26:29.558 --> 00:26:31.358
[all chuckle]

535
00:26:31.492 --> 00:26:35.262
Which reminds me. he texted us
the other day. asked how
the house hunt was going.

536
00:26:36.063 --> 00:26:37.765
Oh. Uh...

537
00:26:37.898 --> 00:26:41.068
Well. poorly.
if I'm being honest.

538
00:26:41.202 --> 00:26:43.572
But that's mostly because
my not-a-side-hustle

539
00:26:43.704 --> 00:26:45.773
-has been keeping me busy.
-Okay.

540
00:26:45.906 --> 00:26:48.577
But I repeat.
this is all just temporary.

541
00:26:48.709 --> 00:26:50.978
You will be visiting me
somewhere new very soon.

542
00:26:51.112 --> 00:26:52.446
Not that we're in any rush.

543
00:26:52.581 --> 00:26:53.747
Thank you.

544
00:26:57.084 --> 00:26:59.653
So. I mean.
as long as he's around.

545
00:26:59.787 --> 00:27:01.523
I think you ought to
make him cook more often.

546
00:27:01.655 --> 00:27:03.424
-Yeah.
-[chuckles] Yeah.

547
00:27:03.558 --> 00:27:05.292
[chuckling]
Well. you know what?

548
00:27:05.426 --> 00:27:09.598
I really do hate
to dine and dash. but I've
gotta get back to the course.

549
00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:12.933
-Should I walk you out?
-Actually. Mel. could you?

550
00:27:13.067 --> 00:27:14.301
Mm-hmm.

551
00:27:14.435 --> 00:27:17.371
I mean. you know. it's
just a... a paperwork thing.

552
00:27:25.479 --> 00:27:27.748
It's not a paperwork thing.

553
00:27:27.882 --> 00:27:30.184
Yeah. No. I... [chuckles]

554
00:27:30.317 --> 00:27:33.354
I'm a detective. I. uh...
I detected that.

555
00:27:34.623 --> 00:27:37.791
I don't want
to create problems.
but I couldn't help picking up

556
00:27:37.925 --> 00:27:40.161
that you don't exactly
love him living here.

557
00:27:41.328 --> 00:27:43.598
-I didn't say that.
-No. you did not.

558
00:27:43.731 --> 00:27:48.169
But if that's how you feel.
I just want you to know
that you can call me.

559
00:27:48.302 --> 00:27:49.604
And you would...

560
00:27:49.737 --> 00:27:54.141
I would tell R.J. that I think
he needs a different situation.

561
00:27:55.009 --> 00:27:57.646
I want the best for
everyone that I supervise.

562
00:27:57.778 --> 00:27:59.614
I'm rooting for all of 'em.

563
00:28:00.114 --> 00:28:03.851
But successful reintegration
into society is complicated.

564
00:28:04.318 --> 00:28:07.656
And it shouldn't cost others
their own happy home.

565
00:28:09.823 --> 00:28:11.492
You decide you want him gone?

566
00:28:12.693 --> 00:28:14.094
Gimme a call.

567
00:28:14.228 --> 00:28:16.997
I'll be the bad guy.
and no one else
would need to know.

568
00:28:17.131 --> 00:28:19.700
-Call it a professional
courtesy.
-[chuckles]

569
00:28:19.833 --> 00:28:21.001
-Thank you. Thank you.
-Right.

570
00:28:21.135 --> 00:28:22.571
-Good night.
-Good night.

571
00:28:43.724 --> 00:28:44.792
How'd it go?

572
00:28:44.925 --> 00:28:48.028
Well... [sighs]
...you win some. you lose some.

573
00:28:48.729 --> 00:28:52.099
Your client's doctor
was unwilling to prescribe
human growth hormone

574
00:28:52.233 --> 00:28:55.637
to satisfy my curiosity on what
might grow when you take it.

575
00:28:55.769 --> 00:28:56.804
Okay.

576
00:28:57.338 --> 00:28:58.739
On the other hand...

577
00:28:58.872 --> 00:29:02.042
Hey! [chuckles]
You got the file. Good work.

578
00:29:02.176 --> 00:29:05.547
Yeah. little lady running
the records room had
to abandon her station

579
00:29:05.680 --> 00:29:08.983
when the toilet in the restroom
very mysteriously began
to overflow.

580
00:29:13.521 --> 00:29:15.789
-Is that not the copy
you're looking for?
-No.

581
00:29:15.923 --> 00:29:17.925
No coffee ring on Page 16.

582
00:29:18.058 --> 00:29:21.095
Plus. every one of
these pages is marked
"for internal use only."

583
00:29:21.762 --> 00:29:24.633
They must have done
that when the doctor took
Bryce on as a patient.

584
00:29:24.765 --> 00:29:28.603
So. wherever the blackmailer
laid his hands on
Bryce's records...

585
00:29:28.737 --> 00:29:30.271
-Yeah. he didn't do it here.
-Okay.

586
00:29:30.404 --> 00:29:32.906
-[phone ringing]
-Hey. Cath. What's up?

587
00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:35.577
[Catherine] <i>Hey. I was</i>
<i>in our assignment meeting</i>
<i>at the</i> Herald <i>this morning</i>

588
00:29:35.710 --> 00:29:38.412
when a familiar
name popped up. Sonny Tedesco.

589
00:29:38.546 --> 00:29:40.749
He's your client's old friend
from San Francisco. right?

590
00:29:40.881 --> 00:29:42.816
Yeah. I mean. well.
Bryce thinks they were friends.

591
00:29:42.950 --> 00:29:44.818
I'm not so sure he isn't
the blackmailer though.

592
00:29:44.952 --> 00:29:46.688
<i>Yeah. he isn't.</i>

593
00:29:46.820 --> 00:29:50.157
He was executed out
in Sunrise this morning.
gunned down in his doorway.

594
00:29:50.291 --> 00:29:52.092
What?

595
00:29:52.226 --> 00:29:53.994
<i>Whoever did it wrote</i>
<i>the Chinese symbol</i>
<i>for "thief" on the house.</i>

596
00:29:54.128 --> 00:29:56.263
I thought you'd wanna
let your client know.

597
00:29:56.731 --> 00:29:58.832
Looks like someone
brought the Triad to town.

598
00:30:10.811 --> 00:30:11.845
[gasps]

599
00:30:11.979 --> 00:30:14.381
[chuckling] Bryce.
Geez. you scared me.

600
00:30:16.817 --> 00:30:18.285
-Guys?
-[R.J. sighs]

601
00:30:18.419 --> 00:30:20.287
[Bryce] Are you the one
that's been doing this. Alan?

602
00:30:20.421 --> 00:30:21.955
Did you give Josh up
to the Triad?

603
00:30:22.657 --> 00:30:24.158
Who to the what. now?

604
00:30:24.291 --> 00:30:27.061
Josh. My friend Josh!

605
00:30:27.194 --> 00:30:31.265
Did you have him killed?
Was it some sort of
a-a warning to me? Why?

606
00:30:31.398 --> 00:30:33.635
Bryce. please... [stammers]
...I don't understand.

607
00:30:33.768 --> 00:30:36.771
Bryce was keeping
medical records
in the cabinet over there.

608
00:30:36.904 --> 00:30:38.839
They're connected to everything
that's going on

609
00:30:38.972 --> 00:30:40.274
between him and his family.

610
00:30:40.407 --> 00:30:43.143
We came in here this morning
to get them. They're gone.

611
00:30:43.277 --> 00:30:45.379
I don't understand.
Medical records?

612
00:30:45.513 --> 00:30:48.449
Bryce. buddy. this is crazy.
I would never do anything
to hurt you.

613
00:30:48.583 --> 00:30:50.719
[Bryce]
You are the only one who's
in this office unaccompanied.

614
00:30:50.851 --> 00:30:52.620
-What are you talking about?
-Bryce.

615
00:30:52.754 --> 00:30:55.356
-No one else even has a key.
-Bryce. wait. Stop.

616
00:30:55.489 --> 00:30:58.892
That-that doorjamb
looks like it was repaired
pretty recently.

617
00:30:59.026 --> 00:31:01.328
-So what?
-So was there
a break-in in here?

618
00:31:01.462 --> 00:31:03.832
If there had been.
do you think I wouldn't
have mentioned it to you?

619
00:31:03.964 --> 00:31:07.736
He's right.
That's not from a break-in.
It was the firefighters.

620
00:31:07.868 --> 00:31:09.804
Wait. what...
what firefighters?

621
00:31:09.937 --> 00:31:12.741
It was. like. a month ago
when you were up in DC
for that conference.

622
00:31:12.873 --> 00:31:15.543
Some kids got
into the storefront
downstairs one night.

623
00:31:15.677 --> 00:31:17.579
let off some fireworks
as a prank.

624
00:31:17.712 --> 00:31:20.080
When I got in in the morning.
there were firemen all over.

625
00:31:20.214 --> 00:31:22.817
They forced their way in
to make sure no embers got in.

626
00:31:22.950 --> 00:31:25.953
-Why didn't you
tell me about that?
-I don't know. Why would I?

627
00:31:26.086 --> 00:31:29.089
Uh. I-I called the handyman.
He fixed the jamb.
That was it. Who cares?

628
00:31:29.223 --> 00:31:31.593
If you don't believe me.
go downstairs and see
for yourself.

629
00:31:31.726 --> 00:31:33.460
[♪ suspenseful music plays]

630
00:31:35.295 --> 00:31:38.065
[Bryce]
These idiot kids could have
burned down the whole building.

631
00:31:38.198 --> 00:31:40.000
I'm not so sure it was kids.

632
00:31:41.068 --> 00:31:42.871
All this could have
been staged as cover

633
00:31:43.003 --> 00:31:46.106
for someone to get upstairs
and go through your files.

634
00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:47.941
The guy who's been
tormenting us.

635
00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.077
If he was the one
that busted through the door.

636
00:31:50.210 --> 00:31:52.212
there'd be no way to tell
after the firefighters
came through.

637
00:31:52.346 --> 00:31:53.848
Yeah. that's one possibility.

638
00:31:54.314 --> 00:31:55.750
Is there another one?

639
00:31:56.216 --> 00:31:59.086
What if the guy that
was trying to get upstairs
was one of the firefighters?

640
00:32:00.954 --> 00:32:04.759
Positions. positions.
All right. we got one down.
play at first.

641
00:32:04.893 --> 00:32:06.293
Here we go. Look alive. Brooks.

642
00:32:06.861 --> 00:32:10.431
Charge it.
charge it. charge it. Play!
Finish the play to first!

643
00:32:10.565 --> 00:32:13.400
Yes! Thataway to be!
Thataway to be!

644
00:32:16.437 --> 00:32:19.273
[sighs] Dale.
do you mind taking
over for a minute?

645
00:32:23.845 --> 00:32:24.945
Everything all right?

646
00:32:25.914 --> 00:32:28.783
Yeah. I just want
to let you know.
Bryce and his family.

647
00:32:29.584 --> 00:32:31.653
they won't be there
when you get home tonight.

648
00:32:31.786 --> 00:32:33.588
You find the person
who's messing with him?

649
00:32:34.121 --> 00:32:35.890
In a manner of speaking.
yeah. I did.

650
00:32:38.760 --> 00:32:40.895
How long you been
a firefighter. Vince?

651
00:32:42.564 --> 00:32:44.833
Yeah. I saw
your T-shirt yesterday.

652
00:32:45.299 --> 00:32:47.769
<i>"Fort Lauderdale's Bravest."</i>
<i>Had the logo and everything.</i>

653
00:32:47.902 --> 00:32:50.204
You lit that car on fire
the other night.

654
00:32:51.071 --> 00:32:54.174
And later you came back with
the rest of your company
to put it out.

655
00:32:55.042 --> 00:32:57.512
All so you could walk through
the front door in a respirator.

656
00:32:58.145 --> 00:33:00.113
leave the blackmail demand
without anyone noticing.

657
00:33:00.247 --> 00:33:02.717
Hey. Denny.
get your glove down.

658
00:33:03.518 --> 00:33:06.855
Pulled the same trick
so you could get into
Bryce's office a month ago.

659
00:33:06.987 --> 00:33:10.123
Set off some fireworks.
so your company
would get called in.

660
00:33:10.257 --> 00:33:12.760
Obviously. that's when
you got his medical records.

661
00:33:12.894 --> 00:33:14.161
Were you looking for him?

662
00:33:15.162 --> 00:33:17.966
Did you already have
an idea that Bryce
wasn't who he said he was?

663
00:33:18.098 --> 00:33:20.501
Something about Bryce
just never added up.

664
00:33:20.635 --> 00:33:23.771
So what? You went
looking for secrets?
You hit the mother lode?

665
00:33:23.905 --> 00:33:27.207
See. what I don't understand.
what Bryce doesn't
understand. is why.

666
00:33:27.341 --> 00:33:28.375
Why?

667
00:33:29.176 --> 00:33:31.713
He says you guys weren't close.
just pals through coaching.
but this?

668
00:33:31.846 --> 00:33:34.047
This is something you do
to someone you hate.

669
00:33:34.181 --> 00:33:36.518
That a boy! [applauding]
That's what I'm talking about.

670
00:33:36.651 --> 00:33:38.185
That right there. you see that?

671
00:33:38.318 --> 00:33:40.855
Brooks is a natural shortstop.

672
00:33:40.989 --> 00:33:44.692
Not an outfielder.
shortstop. [chuckles]

673
00:33:47.027 --> 00:33:50.532
Vince. are you saying you did
all this so Brooks could take
over Henry's position?

674
00:33:50.665 --> 00:33:52.600
-Is that what you're saying?
-Don't get me wrong. okay?

675
00:33:52.734 --> 00:33:54.702
Henry. he's a huge talent.
but he could play anywhere.

676
00:33:54.836 --> 00:33:57.070
Shortstop is for Brooks.

677
00:33:58.806 --> 00:34:02.010
Do you know how early
kids get scouted these days?

678
00:34:02.142 --> 00:34:03.778
And I don't mean pros.

679
00:34:03.912 --> 00:34:07.849
I'm talking traveling teams.
sports academies.
even some colleges.

680
00:34:07.982 --> 00:34:11.151
The places that put you
on the path to the pros.

681
00:34:12.319 --> 00:34:16.423
No way should Bryce get
to take that away from my son.

682
00:34:18.091 --> 00:34:20.728
So what. you go
and kill his ex-partner?

683
00:34:20.862 --> 00:34:23.463
Yeah. that's right.
I know you didn't sic
the Triad on him.

684
00:34:24.064 --> 00:34:26.601
I know you killed him yourself.

685
00:34:26.734 --> 00:34:28.468
<i>The paint you used to</i>
<i>draw the symbol on his house</i>

686
00:34:28.603 --> 00:34:30.905
<i>was the same paint used</i>
<i>on the Danners' garage.</i>

687
00:34:32.040 --> 00:34:34.509
The Danners were told to run.

688
00:34:35.208 --> 00:34:39.514
Hell. I took them in
so they could hear me
telling them. "Guys. I'd run."

689
00:34:40.582 --> 00:34:44.217
But they had you in their ear
telling them that you'd help.

690
00:34:44.986 --> 00:34:47.922
Maybe they needed to
see what could happen.

691
00:34:51.793 --> 00:34:52.961
It's funny.

692
00:34:53.595 --> 00:34:56.965
I wonder why you just didn't
take this all to the cops.

693
00:34:57.865 --> 00:35:00.969
Oh. right. You can't.

694
00:35:01.970 --> 00:35:03.938
'Cause you know
the first thing that
I'd start doing

695
00:35:04.072 --> 00:35:06.708
is talking about
who Bryce really is.

696
00:35:07.374 --> 00:35:08.408
Loud.

697
00:35:09.010 --> 00:35:12.780
So loud. they'd hear it
all the way in San Francisco.

698
00:35:16.718 --> 00:35:18.720
Denny. come on.
Don't be afraid of the ball.

699
00:35:18.853 --> 00:35:20.354
It ain't gonna hop up
and bite you.

700
00:35:32.232 --> 00:35:33.367
God!

701
00:35:33.500 --> 00:35:35.003
[Mel sighs]

702
00:35:38.940 --> 00:35:41.341
I didn't mean to scare you.
but I have to tell you
something.

703
00:35:41.475 --> 00:35:44.112
If it's that you're moving out.
I promise my heart will go on.

704
00:35:44.812 --> 00:35:46.114
No. it's not that.

705
00:35:52.587 --> 00:35:56.057
So this firefighter.
you like him for the murder

706
00:35:56.189 --> 00:36:00.728
out in Sunrise this morning.
but we even question him
about it.

707
00:36:00.862 --> 00:36:02.530
and he'll start screaming
from the rafters

708
00:36:02.664 --> 00:36:05.332
that your client has
a Triad bounty on his head?

709
00:36:05.465 --> 00:36:06.534
Yeah. that's right.

710
00:36:06.668 --> 00:36:08.870
That'll get him killed.
his wife. his kids.

711
00:36:09.436 --> 00:36:11.371
-And yet...
-And yet he killed someone.

712
00:36:11.506 --> 00:36:14.942
-Mm-hmm.
-Someone he barely knew
for no reason.

713
00:36:15.076 --> 00:36:19.147
If you were hoping I would know
some way to put this guy away
and keep him quiet...

714
00:36:20.848 --> 00:36:22.182
But you're right.

715
00:36:22.315 --> 00:36:24.819
What this guy did can't stand.

716
00:36:26.486 --> 00:36:28.690
I have a friend. ex-WITSEC.

717
00:36:28.823 --> 00:36:30.558
She might have some ideas on
how to help the family--

718
00:36:30.692 --> 00:36:33.061
No. no. no. They shouldn't have
to relocate. That's the thing.

719
00:36:34.194 --> 00:36:37.197
That'd be like asking you
and Cath and Sofia to relocate.

720
00:36:38.032 --> 00:36:41.035
[exhales]
And what they have.
what you have...

721
00:36:42.036 --> 00:36:44.706
no one should be able to take
that away from them. No one.

722
00:36:49.143 --> 00:36:51.311
And yet. Triad.

723
00:36:51.445 --> 00:36:52.714
Yeah.

724
00:36:52.847 --> 00:36:55.415
Think about what it would
be like for your clients.

725
00:36:55.550 --> 00:36:59.053
seeing those guys in your sleep
for the rest of your life.

726
00:36:59.187 --> 00:37:01.989
How would you do any of
the things you want to do.

727
00:37:02.123 --> 00:37:04.291
knowing they could be
around the next corner?

728
00:37:06.994 --> 00:37:08.096
Yeah.

729
00:37:09.197 --> 00:37:11.099
How would you do
the things you want to do?

730
00:37:21.341 --> 00:37:22.510
Over here.

731
00:37:28.883 --> 00:37:31.586
I'll admit I was surprised
to hear from you this morning.

732
00:37:31.719 --> 00:37:34.088
Thought we said
all we had to say yesterday.

733
00:37:34.222 --> 00:37:35.923
[chuckles]

734
00:37:36.057 --> 00:37:38.860
Well. you know. I thought
that conversation was
a little one-sided.

735
00:37:39.459 --> 00:37:42.697
Plus. I wanted to show you
these. Take a seat.

736
00:37:45.733 --> 00:37:46.934
[clears throat]

737
00:37:48.368 --> 00:37:49.604
Oh. Jesus.

738
00:37:49.737 --> 00:37:51.639
Yeah. crime scene photos.

739
00:37:52.405 --> 00:37:54.407
Different guys in
different parts of the country.

740
00:37:54.542 --> 00:37:56.978
all killed by
Triad execution squads.

741
00:38:00.313 --> 00:38:03.416
They are... [chuckles]
...a creative bunch.
aren't they?

742
00:38:04.118 --> 00:38:05.186
See these two?

743
00:38:08.656 --> 00:38:10.792
They were killed in prison.
That's important. Vince.

744
00:38:11.259 --> 00:38:13.227
-'Cause that's
where you're going.
-[scoffs]

745
00:38:15.229 --> 00:38:17.665
I thought I made myself
pretty clear yesterday.

746
00:38:18.398 --> 00:38:19.967
I get arrested--

747
00:38:20.101 --> 00:38:23.271
You tell the world
Bryce Danner is really
Bryce Wachtel. I know.

748
00:38:23.403 --> 00:38:24.572
Thing is. you do that.

749
00:38:25.206 --> 00:38:26.874
your picture's going
to end up in here too.

750
00:38:27.008 --> 00:38:28.209
[chuckles]

751
00:38:28.341 --> 00:38:30.310
I'm not the one they think
stole a million bucks.

752
00:38:30.443 --> 00:38:31.579
Oh. but you will be.

753
00:38:31.712 --> 00:38:33.514
That's the other thing
I wanted to show you.

754
00:38:36.184 --> 00:38:37.218
Take a look.

755
00:38:40.755 --> 00:38:42.590
What the hell is
Shadowblade Enterprises?

756
00:38:42.723 --> 00:38:45.325
It's a company you've owned
for almost 15 years now.

757
00:38:45.458 --> 00:38:47.494
the same company
that stole that million bucks
from the Triad

758
00:38:47.628 --> 00:38:49.831
back when Bryce
and his old partner
were doing their books.

759
00:38:49.964 --> 00:38:52.700
[chuckles] I've never even
set foot in San Francisco.

760
00:38:52.834 --> 00:38:54.535
You have. Vince. You have.

761
00:38:55.670 --> 00:38:57.538
At least according
to these papers.

762
00:38:58.773 --> 00:38:59.907
You have.

763
00:39:01.509 --> 00:39:04.846
You really think I'm afraid
of a bunch of phony-ass papers?

764
00:39:04.979 --> 00:39:06.047
You should be.

765
00:39:06.180 --> 00:39:07.515
'Cause if there's one thing

766
00:39:07.648 --> 00:39:09.817
this whole nightmare has made
Bryce very. very good at.

767
00:39:09.951 --> 00:39:11.853
it's falsifying tax
and legal documents.

768
00:39:11.986 --> 00:39:13.688
Think about it.

769
00:39:13.821 --> 00:39:16.791
All the stuff he had
to whip up to start a new life
out here. all the forms.

770
00:39:16.924 --> 00:39:18.960
My friend.
she's a police detective.

771
00:39:19.093 --> 00:39:21.696
she says this is some
of the best work
she's ever seen.

772
00:39:22.997 --> 00:39:24.298
Actually...

773
00:39:24.799 --> 00:39:26.801
[smacks lips] ...she's sitting
right over there.

774
00:39:30.905 --> 00:39:32.740
You see. in a minute.
you're gonna walk over there.

775
00:39:32.874 --> 00:39:35.776
and you're gonna confess to
killing Bryce's old partner
in Sunrise yesterday.

776
00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:39.847
Now you can say it was for...
reasons. whatever.

777
00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:44.252
Anything but the truth.
because this is
important. Vince.

778
00:39:44.952 --> 00:39:46.988
You say one word about Bryce.

779
00:39:47.121 --> 00:39:49.790
anything happens to him
or his family.

780
00:39:49.924 --> 00:39:53.227
a copy of these documents
gets sent to a lawyer
in San Francisco.

781
00:39:53.361 --> 00:39:57.031
a lawyer with serious ties
to the Triad.

782
00:40:04.839 --> 00:40:06.140
[scoffs]

783
00:40:17.351 --> 00:40:18.586
[exhales]

784
00:40:20.821 --> 00:40:23.691
-Turn around. Now.
-[sighs]

785
00:40:26.360 --> 00:40:28.029
[♪ "Swamp Music" playing]

786
00:40:28.162 --> 00:40:29.730
-Yes!
-[Bryce] Whoa!

787
00:40:30.731 --> 00:40:32.066
Henry seems good.

788
00:40:32.199 --> 00:40:33.500
Kids are resilient.

789
00:40:33.634 --> 00:40:35.236
I'm the one that can't wrap
my head around it.

790
00:40:35.369 --> 00:40:37.271
My third-base coach
is a psychopath?

791
00:40:37.405 --> 00:40:38.973
Man. could he run
a good practice.

792
00:40:39.106 --> 00:40:40.141
-[chuckling] Yeah.
-[chuckles]

793
00:40:40.875 --> 00:40:43.144
-How's Molly doing?
-She's getting there.

794
00:40:43.277 --> 00:40:45.680
She didn't love finding out
I hid all that stuff from her.

795
00:40:45.813 --> 00:40:47.748
but you know
she understands. mostly.

796
00:40:48.683 --> 00:40:51.919
Speaking of. uh. wives.
where's your ex's better half?

797
00:40:52.053 --> 00:40:53.788
Uh. I don't know.
Good question.

798
00:40:55.289 --> 00:40:57.558
Hey. everybody having
a good time?

799
00:40:57.692 --> 00:40:58.926
Oh. great time.

800
00:40:59.459 --> 00:41:02.263
And yet here you are.
away from the group.

801
00:41:02.396 --> 00:41:03.798
Mm-hmm.

802
00:41:03.931 --> 00:41:05.599
Want to talk about my offer?

803
00:41:05.733 --> 00:41:06.834
I do. actually.

804
00:41:07.601 --> 00:41:09.637
I wanted to say
thanks but no thanks.

805
00:41:10.271 --> 00:41:11.339
You sure?

806
00:41:13.441 --> 00:41:14.542
Ah!

807
00:41:15.509 --> 00:41:16.544
No.

808
00:41:18.112 --> 00:41:20.414
But you know how they say
you can't pick your family?

809
00:41:21.248 --> 00:41:23.117
I don't think
you can unpick them either.

810
00:41:24.585 --> 00:41:25.653
Yeah.

811
00:41:29.256 --> 00:41:31.158
[all cheer]

812
00:41:31.292 --> 00:41:34.228
[Mel]
That's my girl! [cheering]

813
00:41:34.362 --> 00:41:35.529
That's annoying.
